                     <list>
                        <item xml:id="a1">
                           <locus target="#2r">ff. 2r-2</locus>v: Fragment of a lectionary (excerpt from the Epistle of Paul to the Hebrews, Heb. 3:7-4:3). <quote xml:lang="gez"/>
                           <quote xml:lang="en"/>
                           Written on a leaf originating from an older manuscript (late 14th cent.?).
                        </item>
                        <item xml:id="a2">
                           <locus target="#3r">ff. 3r-4</locus>v: Fragment of Revelation of John (Rev. 3:5-13).<quote xml:lang="gez"/>
                           <quote xml:lang="en"/>
                           Written on leaves originating from an older manuscript (15th cent.?).
                        </item>
                        <item xml:id="e1">- The title is written on the front board with black modern paint.&#xD;
- The internal number of the monastic library (116) is written on <locus target="1r">1r</locus>.&#xD;
- Numbers, partly rubricated, are written by at least two different hands (?; cp. <locus target="15r">15r</locus>, 28r; and <locus target="32r">32r</locus>; one hand is the main, and another one is crude, more recent) in the margins throughout the Ms., indicating the division of the text. &#xD;
- The word ቁ (abbreviation for ቁም) is written by the recent, crude hand throughouot Texts I-VII. &#xD;
- Drawing of a small cross?, in ink: <locus target="31r">31r</locus>.&#xD;
- A few corrections written interlineally(sometimes by the main hand, sometimes by a secondary hand): e.g., <locus target="6vb">6vb</locus>, 9ra, 11ra, 26ra, 33va, 97va.&#xD;
- The word za-mutān is written by a secondary hand in the upper margin: <locus target="15ra">15ra</locus>, 47rb.&#xD;
- Crude notes, writing exercises and drawings by recent hands, in ink, pen and pencil: e.g., <locus target="1r">1r-</locus>v, 5r-v, 72r, 90r, 93v.</item>
                     </list>
